:"1290","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1248":"1248","1312":"1312","1246":"1246","1289":"1289","1310":"1310","1211":"1211","1244":"1244","about 1304":"about 1304","1309":"1309","1317":"1317","Claverley, Shropshire, England":"Claverley, Shropshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Caldecote, Cheshire, England":"Caldecote, Cheshire, England","Heswall cum Oldfiel, Trafford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Heswall, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":0,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":31,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When David de Haselwell was born in 1259, in Cheshire, England, his father, Sir Patric de Hallowell, was 44 and his mother, Agnes de Thurstanton, was 48. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret Vernon. He died in 1310, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1259–1310":"1259–1310","1240–1317":"1240–1317","1241–Male":"1241–Surnud","1242–1289":"1242–1289","1244–Male":"1244–Surnud","1246–Female":"1246–Surnud","1248–Female":"1248–Surnud","1259–Female":"1259–Surnud","1263–1312":"1263–1312","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1215–1309":"1215–1309","1211–Female":"1211–Surnud","1286":"1286","1242":"1242","1263":"1263","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1290":"1290","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1248":"1248","1312":"1312","1246":"1246","1289":"1289","1310":"1310","1211":"1211","1244":"1244","about 1304":"umbes 1304","1309":"1309","1317":"1317","Claverley, Shropshire, England":"Claverley, Shropshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Caldecote, Cheshire, England":"Caldecote, Cheshire, England","Heswall cum Oldfiel, Trafford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Heswall, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1259–1310":"1259–1310","1240–1317":"1240–1317","1241–Male":"12